        <p data-uuid="247dde06fb8b4eb9bb61d423c58ffc72">By 1818 the road reached Wheeling. By 1833 the National Road, as the expansion was called, stretched to Columbus, Ohio. By 1850 it reached all the way to Illinois. The National Road and smaller roads allowed people to travel and transport goods more easily, but land transportation remained slow and costly.</p>
        <p data-uuid="4aa76553b5ed434caebb333c73164a9e"> Boats offered faster and cheaper transportation, but geographic features could also be a challenge along water routes. Many rivers had changes in elevation and, in some places, rapids and waterfalls made boat travel impossible. To help solve these problems, Americans built canals, human-made waterways that connected bodies of water.<br />
        </p>
